"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1921"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1921"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37057"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"317"},{"type":"tags","id":"1091"},{"type":"tags","id":"1554"},{"type":"tags","id":"3310"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"173"},{"type":"contributions","id":"2061"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3796"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/51760"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 66-year-old man presents with a three day history of a dull, gnawing headache. Four weeks previously he had started adjuvant chemotherapy after colonic resection for a Stage IIIB carcinoma. A peripherally-inserted central catheter (PICC) line had been inserted in his right arm which was complicated by an axillary vein thrombosis, resulting in the line being removed and warfarin started. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, there is some tenderness and swelling in the right arm, but no other abnormalities are found. His investigations show: Haemoglobin 139 g/L (135 - 180), white cell count 6.7x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E /L (4.0 \u2013 11.0) and INR 5.6 (1.0 - 1.2). A CT of his head is performed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Metastatic deposit","Extradural haematoma","Subdural haematoma","Intraparenchymal bleed","Cerebral abscess"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe CT demonstrates a \u003Cstrong\u003Esubdural haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E, with a crescentic extra-axial collection of venous blood that is not constrained by cranial sutures. (Image) Its mixed density reflects chronicity: some of the clot has begun to liquefy and so when the patient lies supine for a CT scan, the more liquid components rise to the top while the denser proteinaceous components sink to the bottom. This bleed has resulted from over-anticoagulation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn \u003Cstrong\u003Eextradural haematoma\u003C/strong\u003E would appear as a biconvex (lens-shaped) extra-axial mass, almost always located in the vicinity of the pterion due to the vast majority arising from rupture of the middle meningeal artery, and constrained by sutures. Being arterial bleeds, extradural bleeds are acute emergencies and typically evolve over hours - the three-day history described by this patient would be very atypical.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe remaining options are all typically intra-axial (i.e. within the substance of the cerebral tissue): a \u003Cstrong\u003Emetastatic deposit\u003C/strong\u003E presents as one or more discrete masses with surrounding oedema; a \u003Cstrong\u003Ecerebral abscess\u003C/strong\u003E is classically a ring-enhancing lesion with a fluid level; and an \u003Cstrong\u003Eintraparenchymal bleed\u003C/strong\u003E presents with a hyperdense collection, most commonly in the region of the basal ganglia or thalamus.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Subdural haematoma appears as a crescent-shaped extra-axial collection that is not constrained by suture lines","Subdural haematomas become less dense on CT as they age"],"references":["Feghali J, Yang W, Huang J. Updates in Chronic Subdural Hematoma: Epidemiology, Etiology, Pathogenesis, Treatment, and Outcome. World Neurosurg. 2020;141:339-345. Available at: https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/32593768/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37057"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1921"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"2181"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20991"}]}}},{"type":"media","id":"2181","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/2181"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0dcde06b-c1b3-4637-bcc6-c5fb648c1b06.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/0dcde06b-c1b3-4637-bcc6-c5fb648c1b06.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":365,"height":440}},{"type":"media","id":"20991","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20991"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hycyMSmunuLXKUFWn83DlUjoYgdphM.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/hycyMSmunuLXKUFWn83DlUjoYgdphM.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":365,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37057","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37057"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-08-28T16:37:22+09:30","updatedAt":"2024-08-28T16:38:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1921"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"51760"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student a